# depth_cmd.py — extended teaching content for the cmd track.
# Auto-attached by depth.py. One entry per lesson id.
DEPTH = {
    "cd-1": {
        "title_check": "Files & navigation",
        "sections": [
            {"h": "MENTAL MODEL: DRIVE LETTERS AND PER-DRIVE CURRENT DIRECTORIES", "body": r"""Windows organizes storage differently from Linux: instead of one tree rooted at /, each volume gets a DRIVE LETTER (C:, D:, and so on), and each is its own separate hierarchy. A path like C:\Users\you\file.txt names a drive, then folders separated by BACKSLASHES (not forward slashes), then a file. A subtle but important quirk: CMD tracks a separate "current directory" FOR EACH DRIVE. Typing `D:` switches to drive D at whatever folder you were last in there, and `cd C:\Windows` on drive D changes C's remembered directory without moving you - you must type `cd /d C:\Windows` to change drive AND directory in one step. This per-drive-current-directory behavior surprises everyone coming from Unix. Paths are case-INSENSITIVE (unlike Linux): FILE.TXT and file.txt refer to the same file, though Windows preserves whatever case you used when creating it. Names can contain spaces (Program Files), which forces quoting. The environment variable style differs too: Windows writes variables as %USERPROFILE% (percent signs on both sides) where Linux uses $HOME. Holding these differences - drive letters, backslashes, per-drive directories, case-insensitivity - clearly in mind prevents most of the friction when you move between the two shells, which as a security learner on Windows you will do constantly."""},
            {"h": "MECHANISM: dir, cd, AND THE CORE FILE COMMANDS", "body": r"""`dir` lists a directory, the CMD counterpart to ls. Useful switches: `dir /a` shows hidden and system files (like ls -a), `dir /s` recurses into subdirectories, `dir /b` gives "bare" output (just names, no size/date header - ideal for scripting), `dir /o-d` orders by date descending (newest first), and `dir /p` pauses per screen. `cd` (or `chdir`) changes directory; `cd ..` goes up; `cd \` goes to the drive's root; `cd` with no argument PRINTS the current directory (unlike Unix where bare cd goes home - a real difference). `cd /d D:\work` changes drive and directory together. File operations: `copy src dst` copies a file, `move src dst` moves or renames, `del file` deletes (no recycle bin from CMD - it is gone), `md` (or `mkdir`) makes a directory, `rd` (or `rmdir`) removes an empty one, `rd /s /q folder` removes a folder and its contents quietly. `type file.txt` prints a file's contents (like cat). `ren old new` renames. `cls` clears the screen. Tab completion works for filenames. These map closely to their Unix cousins, so knowing both vocabularies lets you operate on either platform, and on Windows security work you often need CMD because it is always present even when nothing else is installed."""},
            {"h": "WORKED EXAMPLE: ORGANIZING FILES FROM CMD", "body": r"""A short session that mirrors a real cleanup task:
    cd /d C:\Users\you\Downloads
    dir /o-d                          REM list newest-first to see recent files
    md sorted
    md sorted\images
    move *.jpg sorted\images          REM wildcards work: move all jpgs
    move *.png sorted\images
    dir /b sorted\images              REM bare list to confirm
    copy report.docx "C:\My Docs\"    REM quotes: the path has a space
    del /p *.tmp                       REM /p prompts before each delete
The `REM` keyword is a comment in CMD (batch files also allow `::`). Notice `cd /d` to jump drives-and-folder in one move, wildcards (`*.jpg`) expanded by the command itself rather than the shell (unlike Unix, where the shell expands globs before the command sees them - on Windows the individual command does its own wildcard matching, which is why behavior can differ between commands). The quotes around "C:\My Docs\" protect the space. `del /p` adds a confirmation prompt, a wise habit given there is no undo. This kind of quick, keyboard-only file wrangling is exactly what CMD is good for and what you fall back on when a graphical file manager is unavailable or too slow."""},
            {"h": "MECHANISM: CMD VS POWERSHELL, AND WHY BOTH EXIST", "body": r"""Windows ships two shells and you will use both. CMD (cmd.exe) is the old command interpreter: simple, universally present, text-only, with a small built-in command set inherited from DOS. PowerShell is the modern shell built on .NET, and its defining difference is that it passes OBJECTS, not text, between commands. Where CMD's `dir` prints formatted text you must parse, PowerShell's `Get-ChildItem` returns file objects with properties (.Name, .Length, .LastWriteTime) you access directly - `Get-ChildItem | Where-Object {$_.Length -gt 1MB}` filters by a real numeric property, no text-scraping. PowerShell commands are named Verb-Noun (Get-Process, Stop-Service, Copy-Item) and have consistent parameters. It also defines ALIASES so Unix and CMD muscle memory partly works: ls, dir, cat, cp, and cd all map to PowerShell cmdlets, though they behave like the cmdlet, not the original. The rule of thumb: CMD for quick tasks and maximum compatibility (it is on every Windows box, including minimal/recovery environments), PowerShell for anything involving logic, filtering, or automation, because operating on typed objects is vastly more robust than parsing text. Knowing when to reach for each - and that they are genuinely different languages - is a Windows fundamental."""},
            {"h": "FAILURE MODES: DRIVE CONFUSION, SLASHES, AND SILENT OVERWRITES", "body": r"""Windows navigation has its own traps. The per-drive current directory catches everyone: `cd D:\data` from the C: prompt does NOT move you to D - it only sets D's remembered folder while you stay on C; use `cd /d D:\data` or type `D:` then `cd`. Mixing up slashes causes failures: paths use backslashes, but many commands also accept forward slashes for paths while switches use the forward slash (`dir /s`), so `/` is overloaded and context-dependent. Forgetting to quote a path with spaces (`cd C:\Program Files`) breaks because the space splits the argument - `cd "C:\Program Files"` is required. `copy` and `move` silently OVERWRITE the destination without asking (use `/-y` to force a prompt, since the default `/y` behavior in scripts suppresses it). `del` bypasses the Recycle Bin entirely - deleted files are not recoverable through the normal UI - so a wildcard `del *` in the wrong directory is as dangerous as Unix rm. And `rd /s /q` removes an entire tree with no confirmation. As always in a shell, wildcards plus destructive commands demand a pause, and previewing with `dir` before `del *` is the cheap insurance."""},
            {"h": "WHERE THIS GOES: CMD IS THE ALWAYS-PRESENT WINDOWS SHELL", "body": r"""Comfort navigating Windows from the command line is a security prerequisite, because on a Windows target or during incident response the command line is often your most reliable interface - it works over remote sessions, in recovery environments, and where GUIs are locked down or too slow. The next lessons build directly on this foundation: network commands for reconnaissance, live system recon to enumerate a machine, batch scripting to automate, PowerShell for object-based power, and environment/task management for persistence and scheduling. The through-line to hold is that Windows and Unix share concepts (navigate, list, copy, delete, redirect) but differ in surface details (drive letters vs one tree, backslashes vs slashes, %VAR% vs $VAR, per-drive directories, case-insensitivity), and a security professional fluently code-switches between them. Carry forward the Windows-specific gotchas - `cd /d` to change drives, quoting spaces, that del has no undo, and that CMD and PowerShell are different languages for different jobs - and you have the base competence every later Windows technique assumes."""},
        ],
    },
    "cd-2": {
        "title_check": "Network commands",
        "sections": [
            {"h": "MENTAL MODEL: THE MACHINE'S VIEW OF THE NETWORK", "body": r"""Every networked Windows machine holds a set of answers you can query from the command line: what IP addresses it has, which gateway it sends outbound traffic to, what names it has recently resolved, which connections are open, and which programs opened them. Learning the network commands is learning how to interrogate that state. This matters enormously for security work because the first thing you do on any machine - yours under test, or one you are defending - is build a picture of its network posture: its identity (addresses), its reach (routes and connectivity), its exposure (listening ports), and its current conversations (active connections). Windows exposes all of this through a handful of built-in tools that need no installation, which is precisely why they are valuable: on a target you cannot assume any extra software, but ipconfig, ping, netstat, and nslookup are always there. The mental model is that these commands are windows into different layers of the networking stack - addressing, routing, name resolution, and the socket table - and that answering "why can't this reach that?" or "what is this machine talking to?" is a matter of querying the right layer. Building the habit of reflexively checking these on any new machine is a core operational skill."""},
            {"h": "MECHANISM: ipconfig, ping, AND tracert", "body": r"""`ipconfig` shows your network interfaces and their addresses; `ipconfig /all` is the detailed form, revealing MAC addresses, DHCP status, DNS servers, and lease times - the go-to for "what is my full network configuration?". Related switches manage the local name cache: `ipconfig /flushdns` clears the resolver cache (useful when a DNS record changed), `ipconfig /displaydns` shows what is cached, and `ipconfig /release` plus `ipconfig /renew` cycle a DHCP lease. `ping host` tests reachability by sending ICMP echo requests and timing the replies; the round-trip times and any packet loss tell you whether the host is up and how healthy the path is - `ping -t host` pings continuously until Ctrl-C, and `ping -n 4 host` sends a set count. Remember many hosts and firewalls now BLOCK ICMP, so a failed ping does not always mean the host is down - it may just be ignoring pings. `tracert host` (traceroute) maps the router hops between you and a destination by sending packets with increasing TTL and noting where each expires, exposing where a path breaks or slows. Together these answer identity (ipconfig), reachability (ping), and path (tracert) - the first three questions in any connectivity investigation."""},
            {"h": "MECHANISM: netstat AND THE SOCKET TABLE", "body": r"""`netstat` reveals the connection and listening-port state of the machine, and its most useful invocation is `netstat -ano`: -a shows all connections and listening ports, -n shows numeric addresses and ports (no slow name lookups), and -o shows the owning process ID. So `netstat -ano` answers two crucial questions at once - "what ports is this machine listening on?" (potential attack surface) and "what is it currently connected to, and which process owns each connection?" (useful for spotting malware phoning home). You then map a PID to a program with `tasklist | findstr <pid>` or in Task Manager. `netstat -anob` adds the executable name directly but requires administrator rights. Filtering with findstr focuses the output: `netstat -ano | findstr LISTENING` shows only listening sockets, `netstat -ano | findstr :443` finds who is using port 443, and `netstat -ano | findstr ESTABLISHED` shows live connections. For security this is bread-and-butter: enumerating listening services on a box tells you what could be attacked or what has been opened, and reviewing established connections during incident response can reveal an unexpected outbound channel. The modern PowerShell equivalent, `Get-NetTCPConnection`, returns objects you can filter by property, but netstat is universal and always available."""},
            {"h": "MECHANISM: nslookup AND DNS RESOLUTION", "body": r"""`nslookup name` resolves a hostname to its IP address (and vice versa) by querying DNS, letting you confirm what a name points to and which DNS server answered. `nslookup example.com` returns the A/AAAA records; `nslookup example.com 8.8.8.8` queries a SPECIFIC DNS server (here Google's) rather than your default, which is how you check whether different resolvers give different answers - useful for spotting stale caches or DNS-based redirection. You can look up specific record types interactively (set type=MX for mail servers, set type=NS for name servers, set type=TXT for text records often used in verification and security policies like SPF). Reverse lookups (`nslookup 1.2.3.4`) turn an IP back into a name via PTR records. Understanding DNS resolution ORDER matters: Windows checks the hosts file (C:\Windows\System32\drivers\etc\hosts) and its local DNS cache BEFORE querying a server, so a wrong entry in hosts or a poisoned cache can silently redirect a name - which is exactly why `ipconfig /flushdns` and inspecting the hosts file are troubleshooting and security steps. For reconnaissance, DNS enumeration reveals an organization's infrastructure (mail servers, subdomains, name servers), and nslookup is the always-present tool for it, with `dig` (if installed, e.g. via a package) offering richer output."""},
            {"h": "FAILURE MODES: TRUSTING PING, IGNORING PIDS, DNS CACHING", "body": r"""Network diagnosis has classic misreadings. Treating a failed ping as proof a host is down is the biggest: ICMP is frequently firewalled, so a live server can be unreachable by ping while serving traffic normally - test the actual service port (with a tool or PowerShell's Test-NetConnection) rather than relying on ping alone. Reading netstat without the -o/PID column leaves you knowing a port is open but not WHICH process owns it, which is half the story during incident response - always include -o and map the PID. Forgetting that DNS is cached leads to confusion when a record was changed but your machine still resolves the old address; `ipconfig /flushdns` and remembering the hosts-file-then-cache-then-server order resolves it. Running `netstat -anob` (with the executable name) without admin rights silently omits some information. And interpreting `netstat` name-resolved output is slow and can hang on reverse lookups - always add -n for numeric, fast output. A final subtlety: netstat is a snapshot, so a short-lived connection may not appear; for ongoing monitoring you re-run it or use a continuous approach. Knowing these limits keeps you from drawing wrong conclusions from tool output, which under investigation pressure is easy to do."""},
            {"h": "WHERE THIS GOES: NETWORK COMMANDS ARE RECONNAISSANCE", "body": r"""These built-in tools are the foundation of both defensive monitoring and authorized reconnaissance on Windows. The next lesson, live recon, extends them into a broader enumeration of a machine - users, shares, services, and configuration - and network commands are a pillar of that picture. Batch and PowerShell scripting will automate them, letting you sweep many hosts or continuously watch for new connections. For a security career, the ability to quickly establish a machine's network identity, test connectivity intelligently (not naively trusting ping), enumerate listening services as attack surface, map connections to processes, and investigate DNS is daily work in penetration testing, threat hunting, and incident response. Because these tools are always present, they are what you rely on when you have landed on a system with nothing extra installed. Carry forward the key habits - `ipconfig /all` for full config, `netstat -ano` with PID mapping for the socket table, nslookup with an explicit server to bypass caching, and healthy skepticism about firewalled ICMP - and you have a portable, always-available network toolkit for understanding and securing Windows machines."""},
        ],
    },
    "cd-3": {
        "title_check": "Live recon",
        "sections": [
            {"h": "MENTAL MODEL: ENUMERATING A MACHINE YOU JUST LANDED ON", "body": r"""Live recon is the disciplined process of building a complete picture of a Windows system from the command line - who you are on it, what privileges you hold, what users and groups exist, what software and services run, what is scheduled, and how it connects to the network. In authorized security work (penetration testing, red-teaming, or defending and auditing your own systems) this is the first phase after gaining access: you cannot make good decisions about a machine you do not understand. The mental model is a checklist of questions, each answered by a built-in command, that together map the system's identity, its users, its running state, and its configuration. Doing it from the command line matters because it is fast, scriptable, and works where a GUI does not - over a remote shell, on a server, or in a locked-down environment. The commands here are all native to Windows, so they run on any target without installing anything, which is precisely their value: an operator who knows the built-ins can enumerate a system with tools that are guaranteed to be present and that blend in with normal administration. Framing recon as answering a structured set of questions, rather than randomly poking, is what makes it thorough and repeatable."""},
            {"h": "MECHANISM: IDENTITY, USERS, AND PRIVILEGES", "body": r"""Start with who you are and what you can do. `whoami` prints your current user; `whoami /priv` lists your privileges (some, like SeDebugPrivilege or SeImpersonatePrivilege, are significant for what a user can do on a system); `whoami /groups` shows your group memberships, which determine access. `net user` lists local user accounts; `net user <name>` details one account (its groups, last logon, whether it is enabled); `net localgroup administrators` shows who holds local admin - a key question, since admins can do nearly anything. `net accounts` reveals the password policy (lockout thresholds, password age). `query user` (or `quser`) shows who is currently logged on, including remote sessions. For domain environments, `net group /domain` and related commands enumerate domain groups, though those query a domain controller. The security relevance is direct: knowing your own privileges tells you what you can already do; enumerating administrators and privileged groups identifies high-value accounts; and the password policy informs whether credential attacks are feasible. This identity-and-users layer is the first thing an operator establishes, because everything else - what you can read, change, or escalate to - depends on the account context you are operating in."""},
            {"h": "MECHANISM: PROCESSES, SERVICES, AND SOFTWARE", "body": r"""Next, enumerate what is running and installed. `tasklist` lists running processes with PIDs and memory use; `tasklist /svc` maps processes to the services they host; `tasklist /v` adds the owning user and window title. You kill a process with `taskkill /PID <pid> /F` (/F forces it). `sc query` lists services and their state; `sc qc <name>` shows a service's configuration including its binary path and the account it runs as - important because a service running as SYSTEM with a misconfigured (writable or unquoted) path is a classic privilege-escalation avenue that defenders audit and testers check. `net start` lists running services by display name. Installed software can be enumerated from the registry or with `wmic product get name` (though wmic is deprecated on newer Windows, PowerShell's Get-CimInstance or querying the uninstall registry keys replaces it). Scheduled tasks, covered fully in a later lesson, are enumerated with `schtasks /query /fo LIST /v`. The security purpose: running processes and services reveal what the machine does and what security software is present; service configurations expose potential weaknesses; and the installed-software inventory identifies versions that may have known vulnerabilities. This running-and-installed layer turns "a Windows box" into a specific, understood system with known behavior and known weak points."""},
            {"h": "MECHANISM: SYSTEM INFO, SHARES, AND THE NETWORK PICTURE", "body": r"""Round out the picture with system and network context. `systeminfo` dumps the OS version, build, patch level (installed hotfixes), architecture, domain membership, and uptime - the patch list matters because missing patches map to known vulnerabilities, and the build number pins the exact OS version. `hostname` gives the machine name. `net share` lists shared folders on this machine (exposed data or an entry point); `net use` shows connected network shares and can mount new ones. `net view \\host` lists another machine's shares. Combined with the previous lesson's network commands - `ipconfig /all` for addressing, `netstat -ano` for connections and listening ports, `arp -a` for the local ARP cache showing recently contacted machines, `route print` for the routing table - you get the full network posture. `arp -a` is quietly useful: it reveals which other IPs on the local network this machine has recently talked to, hinting at neighbors worth investigating. Environment variables (`set`) reveal configured paths and sometimes secrets. This system-and-network layer places the machine in its environment: which OS and patch level (attack surface), what it shares (data and lateral-movement opportunities), and who it talks to (network neighbors), completing the enumeration."""},
            {"h": "FAILURE MODES: NOISE, STALE DATA, AND CONTEXT ERRORS", "body": r"""Recon has pitfalls both practical and ethical. Practically, some commands need elevation - `tasklist /v` for other users' processes, `netstat -anob` for executable names, many service queries - and silently return partial data without admin rights, so incomplete output may reflect your privilege level, not the machine's true state. wmic is deprecated and absent or disabled on newer systems, so scripts relying on it fail; prefer PowerShell's CIM cmdlets. Some outputs are snapshots (running processes, connections) that miss short-lived activity, and others (arp cache, dns cache) are stale by nature, showing history rather than current truth. Misreading context is easy: a service running as a low-privilege account is not the escalation target a SYSTEM service would be, and confusing local versus domain accounts (`net user` vs `net user /domain`) leads to wrong conclusions. The overriding constraint is authorization: enumeration is a security-relevant activity that must only be performed on systems you own or are explicitly permitted to test - the same commands that audit your own machine are reconnaissance on someone else's, and the difference is permission. Running recon thoughtfully means knowing your privilege level affects the results, preferring current tools over deprecated ones, and operating strictly within authorized scope."""},
            {"h": "WHERE THIS GOES: RECON FEEDS EVERY LATER DECISION", "body": r"""Live recon is the information-gathering phase that every subsequent action depends on, and it ties together the whole CMD track. The navigation and file skills let you explore the filesystem for configuration and data; the network commands supply the connectivity picture; scripting (next lessons) automates the entire enumeration into a repeatable sweep; PowerShell makes it far more powerful through object filtering; and environment/task knowledge covers persistence and scheduling. For a defender, these same commands are how you audit and monitor your own systems - baselining users, services, shares, and connections so anomalies stand out. For an authorized tester, thorough enumeration is what turns access into understanding and understanding into a plan. The professional habits to carry forward are structure and discipline: work through the checklist (identity, users, privileges, processes, services, software, system, shares, network) rather than poking randomly, remember that your privilege level shapes what you can see, prefer current built-ins over deprecated ones, and above all operate only within explicit authorization. Enumeration is where security work becomes systematic, and doing it well from native tools is a foundational competence."""},
        ],
    },
    "cd-4": {
        "title_check": "Script it with .bat",
        "sections": [
            {"h": "MENTAL MODEL: A BATCH FILE IS SAVED CMD COMMANDS", "body": r"""A batch file (.bat or .cmd) is a text file of CMD commands run in sequence - the Windows analogue of a shell script. You create it in any editor, save with a .bat extension, and run it by typing its name or double-clicking. The interpreter is cmd.exe itself, so anything you can type at the prompt works in a batch file, plus a modest set of scripting constructs: variables, conditionals, loops, labels, and subroutines. Batch is old and quirky - its syntax has genuine rough edges the next sections cover - but it is universally available on Windows with zero setup, which is exactly why it endures for quick automation, login scripts, build steps, and glue between tools. Two housekeeping essentials: `@echo off` at the top stops the shell from printing each command before running it (the @ hides that line itself), giving clean output; and `REM` (or `::`) marks comments. Arguments passed to the script are %1, %2, and so on, with %0 the script name and %* all arguments. The mental model is identical to bash scripting - a recipe of commands you would otherwise type - but the dialect is different enough that you must learn batch's specific rules rather than assume Unix habits transfer, because several of them (variable expansion timing especially) behave in genuinely surprising ways."""},
            {"h": "MECHANISM: VARIABLES AND THE set COMMAND", "body": r"""Variables are created with `set`: `set name=world` (crucially, NO spaces around the equals sign, and no spaces are added - `set name = world` creates a variable called "name " with value " world", spaces included). You read a variable by wrapping it in percent signs: `echo %name%`. For arithmetic you need `set /a`: `set /a count=count+1` does integer math. For user input, `set /p answer=Enter value: ` prompts and reads a line into answer. Environment variables the system provides are read the same way: %USERPROFILE%, %COMPUTERNAME%, %PATH%, %TEMP%, %DATE%, %TIME%. Variables set in a batch file are normally LOCAL if you begin with `setlocal` (and vanish when the script ends or hits `endlocal`), which prevents polluting the parent environment - a good default. Quoting differs from Unix: you generally do not quote the value in `set` (the quotes would become part of the value), but you DO quote when using a variable that might contain spaces in a command, e.g. `copy "%src%" "%dst%"`. The single most important thing to internalize about batch variables is that %var% expansion happens when a line is PARSED, which becomes a serious problem inside loops and blocks - the subject of a dedicated section below, because it is the number-one source of batch bugs."""},
            {"h": "MECHANISM: CONDITIONALS, LOOPS, AND LABELS", "body": r"""Batch control flow uses `if`, `for`, `goto`, and labels. Conditionals: `if "%x%"=="yes" (echo confirmed)` compares strings (quote both sides to survive empty or spaced values); `if exist file.txt (...)` tests for a file; `if %n% gtr 5 (...)` compares numbers with word operators (gtr, lss, geq, leq, equ, neq); `if not ...` negates. An `else` must be on the same line as the closing paren: `if cond (...) else (...)`. Loops use `for`: `for %%f in (*.txt) do echo %%f` iterates over matching files (note the DOUBLE percent %%f inside a batch file - a single % is only for the interactive prompt, a constant source of "why doesn't my loop work" confusion); `for /d %%d in (*) do ...` iterates directories; `for /r %%f in (*.log) do ...` recurses; `for /l %%i in (1,1,10) do ...` counts from 1 to 10 by 1; and `for /f "tokens=1,2 delims=," %%a in (file.csv) do ...` parses each line of a file into fields %%a, %%b by a delimiter - the batch equivalent of cut/awk. Labels are lines like `:start`, and `goto start` jumps to them; `goto :eof` exits; `call :sub` invokes a labeled subroutine and returns. Exit codes flow through %errorlevel% (0 usually means success), tested as `if %errorlevel% neq 0 (...)`. This is a full, if clunky, control-flow toolkit sufficient for real automation."""},
            {"h": "MECHANISM: DELAYED EXPANSION - THE %VAR% VS !VAR! RULE", "body": r"""The single most important and most confusing batch concept is WHEN variables expand. By default, %var% is substituted when a line (or a whole parenthesized BLOCK) is PARSED, not when it executes. This breaks inside loops: because the entire `for` block is parsed once before it runs, every %var% inside gets the value the variable had BEFORE the loop started, and updates made during iterations are invisible.
    @echo off
    set count=0
    for %%f in (a b c) do (
        set /a count=count+1
        echo %count%        REM WRONG: always prints 0
    )
The fix is DELAYED expansion: enable it with `setlocal enabledelayedexpansion` at the top, then reference the variable with EXCLAMATION marks instead of percents - !count! - which expands at EXECUTION time, reflecting the current value:
    setlocal enabledelayedexpansion
    set count=0
    for %%f in (a b c) do (
        set /a count=count+1
        echo !count!        REM correct: prints 1, 2, 3
    )
Every batch author hits this once and is baffled. The rule to memorize: outside loops %var% is fine; inside any loop or parenthesized block where the variable CHANGES, you must enable delayed expansion and use !var!. This one rule resolves the majority of "my batch script's variables are wrong" problems."""},
            {"h": "FAILURE MODES: SPACES, SINGLE %, AND SILENT ERRORLEVELS", "body": r"""Batch is unforgiving in specific ways. Spaces around `set`'s equals sign silently create or read the wrong variable name - `set x = 5` makes "x " equal " 5". Using a single % for a for-loop variable inside a .bat file (`for %f`) is a syntax error; batch files require %%f while the interactive prompt uses %f - the same script fails or works depending on where you run it. Not enabling delayed expansion inside a loop (previous section) gives stale variable values that look like the logic is broken. Unquoted variables containing spaces split into multiple arguments, so `copy %src% %dst%` fails when a path has a space - quote them. Comparisons without quotes (`if %x%==yes`) crash when %x% is empty because the line becomes `if ==yes` (malformed); quote both sides. And errors do not stop a batch file by default - it plows on after a failed command, so a script must explicitly check `%errorlevel%` after important commands and `exit /b 1` on failure, or it will happily continue in a broken state (the batch equivalent of forgetting `set -e` in bash). Because batch reports these as wrong behavior rather than clear errors, the discipline is defensive: quote everything, use %% in files, enable delayed expansion in loops, and check errorlevels explicitly."""},
            {"h": "WHERE THIS GOES: BATCH AUTOMATES THE BUILT-INS", "body": r"""Batch scripting turns the individual CMD commands of the previous lessons into automated, repeatable tools - a recon script that runs the whole enumeration checklist, a deployment script, a log-rotation job, or glue that chains several tools together. It composes with everything: file operations, network commands, and live-recon commands all become loop bodies and pipeline stages inside a .bat file, and scheduled tasks (a later lesson) run these scripts unattended. That said, batch's quirks - the expansion-timing trap, weak error handling, awkward string handling - are real, which is why the next lesson introduces PowerShell as the modern alternative for anything complex: PowerShell's object model, proper variables, and real error handling make it far more robust for serious automation. The right instinct is to use batch for short, simple, universally-compatible glue (it is always present, even in minimal environments) and reach for PowerShell when logic grows. Carry forward the batch survival rules - no spaces around set's =, %%var in files, !delayed! expansion inside loops, quote everything, and check %errorlevel% - and you can write correct batch automation while knowing when a task has outgrown it."""},
        ],
    },
    "cd-5": {
        "title_check": "PowerShell basics (and when to use it)",
        "sections": [
            {"h": "MENTAL MODEL: A SHELL THAT PASSES OBJECTS, NOT TEXT", "body": r"""PowerShell's defining idea, and the reason it is so much more powerful than CMD or even Unix shells for many tasks, is that commands pass structured OBJECTS through the pipeline rather than plain text. In bash, `ls | grep big` filters TEXT lines and you scrape fields out with cut/awk. In PowerShell, `Get-ChildItem | Where-Object {$_.Length -gt 1MB}` filters actual file objects by their real numeric .Length property - no parsing, no fragile text-matching. Each object carries typed properties (a file has .Name, .Length, .LastWriteTime, .FullName) and methods you can call. This eliminates the entire class of bugs that come from parsing text output whose format might change. Commands are named consistently as Verb-Noun: Get-Process, Stop-Service, Get-ChildItem, Set-Content, where the verb is from an approved list (Get, Set, New, Remove, Start, Stop) so names are predictable. PowerShell also provides ALIASES so your muscle memory partly works - ls, dir, cat, cp, ps, and cd all map to cmdlets - but they return objects and behave like the cmdlet. The mental shift from CMD/bash is large but liberating: you stop thinking "what text will this print and how do I parse it?" and start thinking "what objects does this return and which properties do I filter and select?", which is a fundamentally more reliable way to automate."""},
            {"h": "MECHANISM: THE PIPELINE, Where-Object, AND Select-Object", "body": r"""PowerShell's pipeline sends objects from one cmdlet to the next. The workhorses are Where-Object (filter) and Select-Object (choose properties or rows). `$_` is the current object in a script block. Filtering: `Get-Process | Where-Object {$_.CPU -gt 100}` keeps processes using over 100 seconds of CPU; the modern shorthand is `Where-Object CPU -gt 100`. Selecting properties: `Get-Process | Select-Object Name, Id, CPU` picks just those columns; `Select-Object -First 5` takes the top five rows. Sorting: `Sort-Object CPU -Descending`. Grouping and counting: `Group-Object`. Formatting for display: `Format-Table` and `Format-List` (use these LAST, only for viewing, because they turn objects into display text that later cmdlets cannot process). Measuring: `Measure-Object -Sum -Property Length` totals a property. So "the five largest files here" is `Get-ChildItem | Sort-Object Length -Descending | Select-Object -First 5 Name, Length` - each stage operates on real objects. `Get-Member` (`| gm`) is the discovery tool: pipe any object to it to list every property and method available, which is how you learn what you can filter and select on. This object pipeline is PowerShell's core, and fluency in Where/Select/Sort/Measure covers most day-to-day needs."""},
            {"h": "MECHANISM: VARIABLES, CMDLETS, AND SCRIPTS", "body": r"""Variables use a $ prefix and hold objects, not just strings: `$procs = Get-Process` stores the whole collection, and `$procs.Count` gives how many, `$procs[0].Name` the first one's name. Types are real - `$n = 5` is an integer, `$s = "hi"` a string, `[int]`, `[string]`, `[datetime]` cast explicitly. Common cmdlets: Get-Content (read a file, returns lines as objects), Set-Content / Add-Content (write / append), Get-ChildItem (list, alias ls/dir), Copy-Item / Move-Item / Remove-Item, Test-Path (does a path exist), Select-String (grep-like search returning match objects), Get-Service / Start-Service / Stop-Service, Invoke-WebRequest (fetch a URL, like curl). Scripts are .ps1 files. Functions use `function Verb-Noun { param($x) ... }`. Conditionals and loops read almost like C: `if ($n -gt 5) { }`, `foreach ($p in $procs) { }`, `while ($cond) { }` - note the comparison operators are words (-gt, -lt, -eq, -ne, -like, -match) because < and > are redirection. Error handling is real, unlike batch: `try { } catch { }` catches terminating errors, and `-ErrorAction Stop` promotes non-terminating ones so they can be caught. A caveat: running .ps1 scripts may be blocked by the Execution Policy (a safety setting), adjustable per-scope. This real language - typed variables, structured error handling, proper functions - is why PowerShell scales to serious automation where batch does not."""},
            {"h": "WORKED EXAMPLE: A REAL PIPELINE VS THE BATCH EQUIVALENT", "body": r"""Find the top three memory-consuming processes and show name and megabytes:
    Get-Process |
      Sort-Object WorkingSet -Descending |
      Select-Object -First 3 Name,
        @{Name='MB'; Expression={[math]::Round($_.WorkingSet/1MB, 1)}}
Read it: Get-Process returns process objects, Sort-Object orders them by the WorkingSet (memory) PROPERTY numerically, Select-Object takes the top three and picks the Name plus a CALCULATED property - the @{Name=...; Expression=...} syntax creates a new column "MB" computed from WorkingSet divided by 1MB and rounded. Everything operates on typed numbers, so the sort and the math are exact. Doing the equivalent in batch would require running tasklist, parsing its fixed-width text output with for /f and delims, converting strings to numbers manually, and sorting by hand - dozens of brittle lines versus this readable pipeline. That contrast is the whole argument for PowerShell: when a task involves filtering, sorting, computing, or selecting based on properties, the object pipeline is dramatically shorter and more robust than text-parsing. For quick file moves or when only CMD is available you still reach for batch, but for anything with logic, PowerShell wins decisively."""},
            {"h": "FAILURE MODES: TEXT HABITS, FORMAT-EARLY, EXECUTION POLICY", "body": r"""The commonest PowerShell mistakes come from bringing text-shell habits. Trying to parse cmdlet output as text (piping to findstr, splitting strings) throws away the objects you were given - filter with Where-Object on properties instead. Using Format-Table or Format-List anywhere but the END of a pipeline breaks it: those cmdlets emit formatting objects meant only for display, so a later Where-Object or Export-Csv sees garbage - format last, filter and select first. Forgetting that comparison operators are words trips people: `if ($x > 5)` REDIRECTS output to a file named 5, it does not compare; use `-gt`. Running a .ps1 and hitting "running scripts is disabled on this system" is the Execution Policy, a safety feature - understand it and set it appropriately for your scope rather than blindly disabling security. Assuming an alias behaves exactly like its Unix namesake (`ls -l`, `cat`, `cp` flags) fails because they are cmdlets with different parameters. And pulling a single object versus a collection matters - a cmdlet returning one item is not always an array, so `.Count` can surprise. The fixes are all one mindset: think in objects and properties, keep formatting to the end, use word operators, and respect the Execution Policy as the security control it is."""},
            {"h": "WHERE THIS GOES: POWERSHELL IS MODERN WINDOWS AUTOMATION", "body": r"""PowerShell is where serious Windows automation and security work happen, and it supersedes batch for anything beyond trivial glue. It ties the whole track together at a higher level: the file operations, network queries, and live-recon enumeration you learned as individual CMD commands all have richer, object-returning PowerShell equivalents (Get-NetTCPConnection, Get-CimInstance, Get-LocalUser) that filter and compose cleanly, and its scripting makes multi-step workflows robust with real error handling. For security specifically, PowerShell is central on both sides - defenders use it for auditing, monitoring, and incident response, while it is also heavily used in offensive tradecraft, which is exactly why understanding it (including logging, the Execution Policy, and constrained modes) is essential for defense. The strategic takeaway is the CMD-vs-PowerShell judgment: batch and raw CMD for maximum compatibility and quick tasks in minimal environments, PowerShell for logic, filtering, computation, and automation of any complexity. Carry forward the object mindset - filter on properties, select columns, format last, use word operators, handle errors with try/catch - and you have the modern Windows shell that professional administration and security both run on."""},
        ],
    },
    "cd-6": {
        "title_check": "Environment, tasks & scheduling",
        "sections": [
            {"h": "MENTAL MODEL: THE ENVIRONMENT AND AUTOMATED EXECUTION", "body": r"""This final lesson covers two related pillars of a running Windows system: the ENVIRONMENT that shapes how programs behave, and the mechanisms that run programs AUTOMATICALLY without a person present. The environment is the set of variables every process inherits - PATH (where the shell looks for executables), TEMP (scratch space), USERPROFILE (your home), and many more - plus system configuration held largely in the registry. Scheduled execution is how work happens on a timer or at an event: the Task Scheduler runs programs at set times, at logon, at startup, or on triggers. Both matter enormously for administration and security. The environment determines what runs when you type a command (PATH order decides which executable wins if two share a name - a real hijacking concern) and passes configuration and sometimes secrets to programs. Scheduling is how legitimate maintenance runs unattended, and equally how persistence is established - a scheduled task that re-launches a program at every logon is a standard persistence mechanism defenders hunt for and testers understand. The mental model is that a Windows system is not just what you type interactively; it is also a configured environment and a set of automated jobs quietly running, and mastering both is what completes your command of the machine."""},
            {"h": "MECHANISM: ENVIRONMENT VARIABLES AND THEIR SCOPE", "body": r"""In CMD you read a variable as %NAME% and set one for the current session with `set NAME=value` (that value disappears when the window closes). PowerShell reads them as $env:NAME and sets a session value with `$env:NAME = "value"`. Viewing: `set` alone lists all in CMD; `Get-ChildItem Env:` does so in PowerShell. The crucial concept is SCOPE and PERSISTENCE. A variable set with `set` or `$env:` lives only in that process and its children - close the shell and it is gone. To set a PERSISTENT variable that survives reboots and applies to future sessions, you use `setx NAME value` (which writes to the registry, but note it does NOT affect the current session - a common confusion, so you often setx AND set), or the System Properties GUI, or PowerShell's [Environment]::SetEnvironmentVariable with a User or Machine target. Variables also have levels: Machine (system-wide, needs admin) versus User (just you), and the effective value your session sees is a merge. PATH is the most important: it is a semicolon-separated list of directories searched left to right for executables, so the ORDER matters - a directory earlier in PATH wins, which is why a malicious or mistaken entry early in PATH can cause the wrong program to run (a "PATH hijack"). Understanding session-versus-persistent and User-versus-Machine scope prevents the frequent "I set it but it did not take" frustration."""},
            {"h": "MECHANISM: THE TASK SCHEDULER AND schtasks", "body": r"""The Windows Task Scheduler runs programs automatically on triggers, controlled from the command line with `schtasks`. Query existing tasks: `schtasks /query /fo LIST /v` gives a verbose list of every scheduled task, its trigger, and the account it runs as - a key enumeration and audit step, since tasks reveal both legitimate maintenance and any persistence. Create a task: `schtasks /create /tn "MyJob" /tr "C:\path\script.bat" /sc daily /st 09:00` schedules script.bat every day at 9am (/tn task name, /tr the program to run, /sc the schedule type - MINUTE, HOURLY, DAILY, WEEKLY, ONLOGON, ONSTART - /st the start time). Run one on demand with `schtasks /run /tn "MyJob"`; delete with `schtasks /delete /tn "MyJob" /f`. Tasks can run under specific accounts, including SYSTEM with `/ru SYSTEM` (needs admin), which is powerful because SYSTEM has full local rights. The security relevance is twofold: defensively, auditing scheduled tasks is essential because a task running a script at every logon or startup, especially as SYSTEM, is a classic persistence and privilege mechanism - reviewing `schtasks /query /v` output for unfamiliar or suspiciously-pathed tasks is routine threat hunting. Offensively (authorized), understanding task creation is part of knowing how persistence works. The older `at` command is deprecated; schtasks is the tool, and PowerShell's ScheduledTasks module (Get-ScheduledTask) offers an object-based equivalent."""},
            {"h": "MECHANISM: THE REGISTRY AND STARTUP LOCATIONS", "body": r"""Much of Windows configuration lives in the REGISTRY, a hierarchical database of keys and values, queried from the command line with `reg`. `reg query HKLM\Software\...` reads a key; `reg add` and `reg delete` modify it (system keys need admin). The registry holds environment variables, installed-software records, and - importantly for security - AUTOSTART locations that launch programs at boot or logon. The classic "Run" keys, HKLM\Software\Microsoft\Windows\CurrentVersion\Run (all users) and the HKCU equivalent (current user), list programs started automatically at logon; enumerating them (`reg query HKLM\Software\Microsoft\Windows\CurrentVersion\Run`) is a standard step in both auditing a machine and hunting for persistence, because malware frequently adds itself there. Other autostart vectors include the Startup folder (`shell:startup`), services set to auto-start, and scheduled tasks. PowerShell reads the registry as a drive: `Get-ItemProperty HKLM:\Software\...`. The security theme is that "what runs automatically on this machine?" is answered by checking scheduled tasks, the Run keys, the Startup folder, and auto-start services together - a persistence-enumeration checklist. Modifying the registry is powerful and risky: a wrong change can break the system, and there is limited undo, so `reg export` a key to back it up before editing is the prudent habit. Understanding the registry as the configuration and autostart backbone completes the picture of how a Windows system is set up and how it launches software."""},
            {"h": "FAILURE MODES: SESSION-ONLY SETS, PATH HIJACKS, TASK CONTEXT", "body": r"""These mechanisms have precise pitfalls. The environment-variable one recurs constantly: `set` (or `$env:`) changes only the CURRENT session, so users expecting a permanent change are surprised the value is gone after closing the shell - use `setx` for persistence, but remember setx does NOT update the current session, so you often need both. Editing PATH carelessly is dangerous: appending with `setx PATH "%PATH%;C:\new"` can TRUNCATE PATH because setx has a length limit and %PATH% may already be long, and a reckless PATH edit can also break the system by dropping essential directories - always back up the value first. Putting a writable or attacker-controlled directory early in PATH enables the wrong executable to run (a hijack), a real security weakness to check for. On scheduling, creating a task without noting the account it runs as leads to wrong conclusions about privilege, and a task with a SYSTEM context is far more significant than a user one. Registry edits are unforgiving - a mistaken delete or a bad value in a critical key can prevent boot, and there is no recycle bin, so export-before-edit is essential. And across all of these, many operations require administrator rights and silently do less without them. The disciplines: distinguish session from persistent scope, treat PATH edits with backup and care, note the run-context of tasks, and back up registry keys before changing them."""},
            {"h": "WHERE THIS GOES: COMPLETING COMMAND OF THE MACHINE", "body": r"""Environment configuration and scheduled execution complete your command-line mastery of Windows, tying together everything the track built. The environment shapes how every command you learned behaves (PATH decides what runs), scripting reads and sets variables, and the Task Scheduler runs your batch and PowerShell scripts unattended - so this lesson turns interactive skill into automated, persistent capability. For security, these are among the most important topics: environment and PATH analysis reveal misconfigurations and hijack opportunities; scheduled tasks, Run keys, the Startup folder, and auto-start services are THE places persistence hides, so enumerating them is core to both defending and auditing systems and to understanding how attackers maintain access; and the registry is the configuration substrate underlying all of it. A defender who can list every autostart vector and every scheduled task, and reason about environment scope and PATH order, can find what does not belong. The professional habits to carry from the whole track: prefer built-in tools that are always present, know the CMD-versus-PowerShell tradeoff, respect the session-versus-persistent and User-versus-Machine scopes, back up before destructive changes, and always operate within authorization. With navigation, networking, recon, scripting, PowerShell, and now environment and scheduling, you have a complete working command of Windows from the terminal."""},
        ],
    },
}
